          <h3>Reason as Extrapolation</h3>
          <p>Reason reaches conclusions. Conclusions need to be reached because not everything can known or confirmed. A conclusion is an extrapolation. An extrapolation is a guess. A guess is a proposal. A proposal is an offering of potential. An offering of potential is something that can't be confirmed true or false ahead of time. Not everything can be known ahead of time, because the future hasn't happened yet. There is always a future, so not everything can be known then. But there is also always a past. The past is shared. Having a shared past means things happened one way underlyingly. Things happening one way underlyingly infers other things happening one way underlyingly will happen. Things happening one way underlyingly inferring other things happening one way underlyingly is extrapolation. Extrapolation also known as reason. Reason also known as guess. Guess mean inferring what true or not from what true or not.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card-grid card-grid--2">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>The Limits of Certainty</h3>
          <p>Knowing everything impossible. Knowing something impossible? Certainty about everything impossible. Certainty about anything, impossible?</p>
          <p>No certainty about anything, impossible. Assumption possible. Guess possible. Proposal possible. Thinking possible. Reason possible. Extrapolation possible. Change possible. Truth possible. False possible. Uncertainty possible. Direction possible. Inconsistency possible.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h3>Believing and Assuming</h3>
          <p>Believing one thing requires believing others.</p>
          <p>Assuming one thing requires assuming others.</p>
          <p>Assuming one thing necessitates assuming others.</p>
          <p>Whether you assume something to be true or false affects whether you believe other things to be true or false, and whether you believe something to be true or false affects whether you assume something to be true or false.</p>
          <p>Believing is therefore assuming, and assuming is believing.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Page 3: Certainty and Inconsistency -->
    <section>
      <div class="card-grid card-grid--2">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Certainty as Effect</h3>
          <p>Therefore it is important to consider how what you believe affects what you assume. And how what you assume affects what you believe.</p>
          <p>This effect can be represented by what we call certainty.</p>
          <p>False certainty exists, and occurs when we don't consider what we assume in order to believe, or what we believe in order to assume.</p>
          <p>Anti-certainty in the domain of reason is also known as logical inconsistency. Certainty and logical inconsistency are therefore inversely correlated.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h3>Logical Inconsistency</h3>
          <p>But what is logical inconsistency? If I were to take a claim, and assume it to be true or false, there would be implications for each case. Implications in this case would mean possible problems and possible solutions. If you were to take a claim, assume it to be true or false, would what you then have to believe in be the opposite of what you may already be believing as a result of assuming something else?</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card-grid card-grid--1">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Classifying Claims</h3>
          <p>Each claim can therefore be represented as either true, false, likely, unlikely, or unknown. The more things you know about what you have to assume to believe a claim, the more certain you can be about what classification makes sense for the claim. If most of what you have to assume to believe a claim can be represented as being true, then the claim can lean towards certain truth, whereas if most of what you have to assume to believe a claim can be represented as being false, then the claim can lean towards certain false. If what you have to assume is a mix of truth and false, likely and unlikely, or currently unknown, then whether that claim is true or false is harder to know with certainty, but at least you are now more certain that you know how certain you can be that your classification is correct.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Page 4: Disagreement -->
    <section>
      <div class="card-grid card-grid--1">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Overlap and Disagreement</h3>
          <p>Overlap can be defined as how many claims you are making where the implications don't match each other. While sitting down with someone, I could say: "we are sitting down". Claim could be true or false, like any other claim, and can be disagreed with, like any other claim.</p>
          <p>The manner in which disagreement is made can be categorized into several distinct categories. Disagreement can be made with the frame: We aren't sitting down we are talking. With the subject: You may be sitting down but I am not. And so on. The important thing here not the specific examples, but that disagreement can also be thought of as a claim, because the disagreement could be either true or false. And if the disagreement can be thought of as true or false, then the disagreement can be thought of as a claim, that can therefore be disagreed with. So therefore nearly anything can be disagreed with, as long as it is something that can be evaluated as to whether it is true or false.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card-grid card-grid--1">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Agree and Disagree</h3>
          <p>But something is missing here. Nearly everything can also be not disagreed with, aka it can be agreed with. So now we have two ways of being able to handle any claim. We could agree, thereby assuming it is correct, right, true, or we could disagree, thereby assuming it is incorrect, false, wrong. Agreeing can also be thought of as the non-contrarian position, while disagreeing can be thought of as the contrarian position.</p>
          <p>With just these two simple principles, assuming wrong and assuming right, we can massively increase the sophistication, depth, and breadth with which we can evaluate the truth of a claim, which we can now treat as a discrete entity.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Page 5: The Obvious and Claims -->
    <section>
      <div class="card-grid card-grid--1">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Nothing is Obvious</h3>
          <p>Even if it may seem obvious that a claim is true, someone, somewhere, in some context, and some perspective, might be able to disagree that the claim is true, and we should not disagree with where they are coming from, because they always will have at least part of their claim be right, if they are operating under good guessing principles, aka logic, analogy, and so on. Also, if we do not allow disagreement with "obvious" frames, we won't be able to examine our assumptions or beliefs as to why we believe it to be the case. Oftentimes if something seems obvious, it actually isn't obvious, it's just that believing the alternative may be uncomfortable, strange, or difficult to grasp.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card-grid card-grid--2">
        <div class="card">
