          <h3>Long Term Planning</h3>
          <p>Notice how this process worked. In order to reach the conclusion that going to the mall was a good idea, she first had to assume a whole bunch of things were right. For just a couple of them, to get an idea, she had to, for instance, assume that living a fulfilling life is a good goal and something she actually wants, and that if she was able to life life how she pleased, then this would enable her to live a fulfilling life. There is another word for this process: long term planning. Believing that going to the mall is a good idea is just a means to an end: that of being able to live a fulfilling life. In order to go from "going to the mall is a good idea" to "being able to live a fulfilling life", she had to do something that I call a goal journey, figuring out how to go from where you are to where you want to be, or how you got to wanting what you want to thinking what you think to acting what you act. But goal journeys can be more sophisticated and non linear. She could have just as easily assumed wrong from the opposite starting claim: Going to the mall is a bad idea. It is likely she is going to reach the same or similar conclusion than if she would have assumed it is true. Being able to assume something is wrong and assume it is right therefore enables thorough space search testing.</p>
